##Confessions of a smoking doctor: I spent five days in isolation

Editor's Note: Dr. Xie Guogang of Shanghai First People's Hospital, signed up on February 1 to support the medical team of Shanghai Public Health Clinical Center. Early Morning 5 o'clock, on duty he received the report of the telephone notice, even home are too late back, rushed to the "battlefield. ". We should know that Dr. Xie Guogang has just finished his six-month work in December, and now he has embarked on a new journey, and it is even more difficult and dangerous.

Remember chatting with Dr. Xie years ago and asking him if he couldn't get another vacation. He replied, always ON CALL. Words can't describe how I feel right now, but as a private citizen, we feel safe and protected by doctors like this.

By Xie Guogang

I signed up as soon as I heard the news that the hospital was setting up a medical team to support the Shanghai Public Health Clinical Center. Professional counterparts, and Communist Party members, in the current situation, no need to mobilize, in the face of danger must go. I just didn't expect that the order to go to war would come so quickly. I received an urgent call from the medical department at more than 5:00 a.m. on the 24-hour shift at the hospital, informing me that I would set out that morning to report to the Shanghai Public Health Clinical Center, it's a battlefield atmosphere where there's no fighting. Home Preparation is too late, let the home hurriedly packed up some daily supplies sent to the hospital.

Our medical team included one doctor and two nurses. Hospital leaders held a brief farewell and condolence ceremony. Director Zhang Min repeatedly told me that I should do a good job of protection, at the same time with their own good professional ability to do a good job of patients with the diagnosis and treatment and psychological counseling. Then we set out on a journey.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A friend asked me if I was scared. Not Really. Fear comes from the unknown. Confidence comes from knowing. Now that we know the infectivity of the virus, as long as the thinking seriously, do a good job of protection, there is no risk of infection.

Another friend said, I'm going to suffer, which is nothing, considering that Professor Zhou Xin, the leader of our discipline, went to Wuhan on New Year's Eve to fight against COVID-19 pneumonia, taking the lead and working tirelessly. In the face of such an example, we do not feel hard.

Arriving at the Shanghai Public Health Clinic, we quickly joined up with the medical team from other hospitals to support us. Public Health leaders have stressed the importance of medical staff to protect themselves as well as to treat patients. If medical staff can not achieve zero infection, then our fight against new pneumonia will not be a complete victory in the future. This is a powerful statement and a very high demand for us. The next big thing is, of course, training in how to put on and off a hazmat suit. In the prevention and treatment of infectious diseases, isolation clothing is the most effective protective measure, not only to protect the health care workers themselves, but also to prevent the spread of pathogenic microorganisms and avoid cross-infection, it is extremely important to master every step and detail of the procedure of wearing and taking off the isolation clothing. The first time to wear isolation clothes inevitably confused, public health infection department teachers both strict and patient, supervision of each of us repeated practice, one by one before clearance. It took an afternoon of training and practice, but it was well worth it. The better prepared we are, the less chance we have of getting infected.

After our own throat swabs came back negative, we spent the night in the ward building and began familiarizing ourselves with the ward environment and patient intake procedures. After entering the ward building, we could not set foot outside the building for the next two weeks. All Work and life were managed in a closed-door way. Of course, the telephone and news were always open and in constant contact with the outside world.

The next day, we were back at work, engaged in an intense battle. The A1 ward building where I work is mainly for patients with mild illness. The Joint Health and Health Commission Expert Group will conduct group video ward rounds for patients every day, while my task here is mainly for routine ward rounds, the patient's condition changes to the expert group, timely detection of severe patients for more active treatment. There is a large amount of paperwork to complete, but also to keep an eye on their management of the patient's test results and changes in the condition, the workload is still considerable. However, the most energy intensive and at greatest risk are those in close contact with patients in isolation wards.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
When a new patient comes in, the patient's history can be collected by phone, but understanding the patient must be done face-to-face in the ward. For each new patient, a physical examination and an electrocardiogram are needed to assess the patient's condition and determine the appropriate course of treatment. Wearing N95 face mask, wearing heavy isolation clothing, in the closed ward work, walking slowly, feeling breathing is very hard, a long time, all over the sweat, goggles a blank. In my experience, this is the most painful work environment, however, here, you can also meet the patients most look forward to.

In our rounds, there are patients who hold you and say, "doctor, you need to see me more! " You need to give gentle relief; there are patients who fidget and ask, "doctor, why is my disease not getting better? " You need to give firm encouragement; Some patients cry because they miss their family members, and you can share the joy with them when they get better.

Though they couldn't see my face, the cold suit seemed to heat up in conversation, and though it was heavy and stuffy, there were countless paramedics willing to dress and carry heavy loads. In this suit, our medics are Ninjas, not to mention humanoids.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"The more difficult the situation, the more we move forward, " Xi said. "It is the doctors who are responsible for helping to tide over the crisis. ". We believe that with our perseverance and strong backing of the country, we will be able to win this fierce new crown pneumonia epidemic of the war!

The writer is a cardiologist in Shanghai First People's Hospital
